With the way Tether is currently tracking amidst the FTX fallout, and even if it becomes "de-pegged" in the future, the overall market cap (undiluted) would be just under $65-billion USD; this should be a much lower market cap, however, there is no way to audit their reserves and so everyone is still speculating that we are in the same type of reality that drove BTC to $69K--we simply are not.

updating given shortened time frame - although there is increased risk appetite recently, that's mostly seen in equities/corporate bonds but not in cryptos. Given the volatility in Tether market cap, I believe it's highly likely that the market cap stays in the 60-70bn range.

Building off from current crowd forecast - but given the time frame (20days) believe there will be minimal volatility in USDT mkt cap. Even the most volatile 20 day change of its mkt cap happened YTD is a ~$11bn move at start of May. I will assume that as a 2SD move - so 95% chance it will be +-$11bn of current mkt cap of $69.5bn. Given a recent uptick in risk appetite for cryptos, will skew my forecast to the upside.
Very close
There has been an average of $1bn in inflows to Tether each month the last three months. If that happens again in the next month, we would be right on the edge of $70bn.
In the last 45 days we've had about $2bn of inflow. With about 75 days left in this question and only about $2bn away from $70bn cap, it's increasingly likely we actually get there.

https://assets.ctfassets.net/vyse88cgwfbl/2xJyKdUKicdRUWpC9buRWR/544a579335ae65ed0e08c162c5a2c5d9/Std_ISAE_3000R_Opinion_30-6-2022_RC134792022BD0303.pdfTether audit from BDO is out. Commercial paper holdings down to about 10% of Tether assets. Assets exceed liabilities. They are also promising to eliminate commercial paper by end of year which should do away with the vast majority of their financial risk. In any case it looks like over 2/3 of Tether's assets are in highly liquid/safe assets meaning they could cash out to about a $20bn market cap without any risk, and probably beyond that.

Based on the "Dutch Tulip Mania" which is driving the sentiment of investors at the moment, being comprised of mainly retail investors, the only cure for such unprincipled and baseless valuations is the reality of the overall economy in which these types of niche markets rest. We are already seeing labor force numbers reporting almost half of what was estimated for April/May, and those "unicorns" which are key performers in other arena markets (e.g., DJI, NASDAQ, S&P 500) are now issuing earnings warnings or cautionary guidance about future earnings potential; I feel like Tesla was among the first "industry leader" to experience the reality of the current market dynamics, being that the conflict in Ukraine, among other issues, will most certainly impact their ability to produce things like batteries or even get the necessary supplies to their vendors for other critical components needed before their cars are delivered--all of this is only now being priced into their stock even though the invasion has been ongoing since Feb 22, 2022, so it is clear that speculators are still freely sipping on whatever gave them their current hangover while hoping that the "hair of the dog" will ease momentary discomfort without too much bite.
- Currently valued at 72 billion

This is a very difficult forecast. I'm very uncertain how to base rate this, much less guess what the value may be in the future. I am going to take the current value of Tether as a base rate - that is, I assume that without outside forces acting to change the value, the value should stay the same.

People have been predicting the imminent collapse of Tether for over 5 years and it hasn't happened. The NYAG completed its investigation last year and Tether is still standing. They are backed by $$$, treasuries, and corporate bonds. Problem is that like 40% of that is Bitfinex corporate bonds, meaning Tether is toast if Bitfinex ever goes under. But the odds of that happening in the next 6 months is very low. Chances are the market cap of Tether will be close to what it is now in 6 months. Currently people are exchanging Tether for USD after the Luna panic, and I don't take a strong opinion on how long that will continue, but most likely it will not go on all that much longer or be the end of Tether.
Tether is a Ponzi scheme that is being criminally investigated by the NYAG. Tether has always refused to be audited, claiming that they “don’t want to give away the secret sauce.”
